so its total assets are $2,000.

00:00:14.390 --> 00:00:15.790
And then that should be the same

00:00:15.790 --> 00:00:17.590
as its liabilities and equity.

00:00:17.590 --> 00:00:21.530
And we see here that it has
$2,000 in demand deposits,

00:00:21.530 --> 00:00:23.950
that's a liability 'cause
people can come to the bank

00:00:23.950 --> 00:00:25.510
and say, "Hey, I want that money."

00:00:25.510 --> 00:00:27.110
These are checkable deposits so they

00:00:27.110 --> 00:00:29.460
could even try to withdraw that money.

00:00:29.460 --> 00:00:32.390
And since all of that
$2,000 is on the liability

00:00:32.390 --> 00:00:34.580
side there's no equity right over here.

00:00:34.580 --> 00:00:37.020
These two should sum up to $2,000,

00:00:37.020 --> 00:00:39.363
the same as you have on your assets side.

00:00:39.363 --> 00:00:44.363
Assume that the required
reserve ratio is 10%.

00:00:44.540 --> 00:00:46.930
And just as a review, that's
the percent of deposits

00:00:46.930 --> 00:00:49.286
that the bank needs to keep as reserves

00:00:49.286 --> 00:00:52.766
and we can see that it's at
that reserve ratio right now.

00:00:52.766 --> 00:00:57.546
It has $2,000 in deposits
and so it needs to keep 10%

00:00:57.546 --> 00:01:01.720
as reserves, 10% of $2,000 is $200,

00:01:01.720 --> 00:01:04.845
so it's at its minimum reserves already.

00:01:04.845 --> 00:01:09.300
Part A says what is the
dollar value of new loans

00:01:09.300 --> 00:01:13.610
that First Superior
Bank can make, explain.

